<br>
It is sad that there is so much momentum for the holy rule that an efficient group must contain one or more tanks, a cleric, and some form of slower. Part of the fault is that the designers have made content suited toward the traditional tank/healer/slower group; while most of the fault is because people are often too lazy to try something different (even if it means a little risk).<br>
<br>
PoP mobs hit insanely hard and fast and have considerable amount of HPs. The obvious way to address this content is the holy trio (tank, healer, slower). Sure it is possible to use multiple pets, kite, ping-pong, chain stun, and a variety of other techniques instead of the holy trio... these &quot;non-traditional&quot; group formations/tactics are not widely practiced, offer some risk, and/or require that your group mates have a little bit of grey matter and patience.<br>
<br>
Most of the time you can indeed take the initiative and form a group yourself. As group leader you have the choice to invite the holy trio, or you can break the mold and improvise with a non-traditional group. I generally warn people when I invite them however that the group may be non-traditional and may incur some stress, but it can be a lot more fun than a typical grind group. If I go for a traditional group, I change my warning -- that they may have to wait a bit until we find the tank/cleric/slower.<br>
<br>
While it is nice to have a cleric in the group... you can live without them. Slow the mob, snare it, send in the pets/tanks, have everyone stun, everyone root when necessary, and blast it hard. If you have a Cleric, tell them to load their stuns and nukes as well... You'll be surprised at how little mana will be needed for healing. If you have some room to spread the nukers out, a little communication will enable you to get the mob to ping pong like a game of frisbee.<br>
<br>
If you have the room, a safer approach may be to do some kiting. I can't solo kite many PoP mobs because their HPs surpass the amount of damage I can unload with a full bar of mana. But what if I had a partner to finish them off when I ran out, or to help when I got into trouble. Now how about 5 buddies to help pick up the slack. Imagine a group running around in a triangle, stopping at each point ahead of their snared mob to simultaneously cast 6 nukes. Booyah. Or take turns, have only 1 or 2 kiting while the other group members sit on the bench. As each kiter runs out of mana, they tag a bench warmer who finishes them off. Rotate through the group allowing the oom to med and those with mana to kite.<br>
<br>
These caster-heavy groups do not require any sort of tank (in fact sometimes tanks complicate these tactics). So you don't wait all day for a tank. If you don't need a tank, you may no longer feel pressured to find a cleric and slower. Sure it is safer to have a healer and slower, but if you're group is good, the mob will never touch anyone.<br>
<br>
What about pulling? Ocassionally the FD puller is needed. You might be surprised though how a little bit of harmony or a long-range, low-agro (cancel magic) spell will work. Root, atone, mez, charm, etc are all fine ways to deal with multi pulls (let us not forget the beauty of AEs as well).<br>
<br>
Do you not agree that all these group tactics are as valid as the &quot;traditional&quot; group? Yes? Then we need to market these types of groups. It would be great if SOE helped us market these groups though!<br>
<br>
If Clerics are so crucial to a group and imbalance class selection for groups... why not have groups take a small experience penalty for having a cleric in the group? That might make people think twice about forming a traditional group. Maybe a bit too harsh? Then how about penalties for large heals (e.g. raise the non-raid-mob agro for CH, increase the mana cost, etc)? Having several hybrid healer classes spreading out agro with small heals would increase their grouping karma -- and Clerics would finally be able to do more than just heal. With healing penalties kicked up people might respect the old saying, &quot;The faster you burn em down, the less you have to heal.&quot;<br>
<br>
The &quot;not-so-group-attractive classes&quot; have a commonality in DPS... How about designing more content for the DPS caster group? Make the creatures hit slower, softer, but counter that with something bad happening if you don't kill them within a certain amount of time: e.g. they spawn another mob (annoying green mob), they heal themselves, they become increasingly higher in AC and/or resistance (only while under attack), etc.<br>
<br>
If the non-traditional groups are not popular because of the risk, efficiency (pull rate), or most likely because of the amount of non-laziness it takes to find a good non-traditional group, then SOE should award these non-tradtional groups with an experience bonus.<br>
<br>
Why fix one of the broken group classes when you can fix a dozen of them?<br>
<br>
I fear if non-traditional groups took off, the Warriors would really suffer... They are already struggling in the traditional groups due to their difficulties with holding agro.<br>
<br>
Personally though, I'll take the fun of a non-traditional group any day to the boring grind of watching a tank go toe to toe with each mob. <p><!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
